 I'll go along with the earlier post which said that at present, it's a waste. It should be drastically reorganized.<br>
 Get it out of daily operations -which kills the Shuttle and ISS, since no business organization would operate the things as they're designed; deliberately over-complex &amp; expensive.<br>
<br>
 The old saying is that &quot;governments build roads, companies build &amp; operate trucks&quot; says it.<br>
 NASA should help innovate technologies, and maybe help operate &quot;space highways&quot; like launch complexes, laser thermal lifters, etc.<br>
<br>
 Now as to exploitation:<br>
 If companies go bankrupt, trying to expand into space, why should anyone feel sorry for them? They were obviously fools, trying to bite off more than they can chew, and 'Economic Darwinism' caught up with them. Of course the obverse is what we have now, with no investors willing to take any risks in space.<br>
 The point is that the government should do something, even a little bit, to encourage it. Some companies will be able to make responsible risk choices, and make it big.<br>
<br>
 There is a treaty forbidding laying claim to the whole Moon. You can claim, and you must be responsible for, the area immediately around your equipment. This only needs modification so that a company could, for instance, claim the entire 300 meter asteroid they're dragging back, and can be assured of being able to make profits when they can get metals to markets.<br>
 Stipulating such things in treaty law is one of the things government should be doing. There's evidence that the US gov't specifically wanted those bits in the treaty deliberately to cause loss of interest in space (Zubrin reported on findings from an NSS member using FOIA, to discover white house memos to the State dept in 1966)<br>
<br>
Pizza Hut should be able to buy advertising space on the side of a rocket, and whoever builds a piece of a private space mission vehicle should be able to have their logo on video feed and crew suit patches.<br>
I personally feel that it's right that nobody should get their corporate logo on a huge billboard in orbit (a business idea shot down by legislation recently. It would have orbited every 120 minutes, and been the size and brightness of the full Moon).<br>
 Other than some limitations, we should be going all out to encourage space exploitation. Get space industries going, and then discourage exploitation of the Earth &amp; biosphere?!? I'd rather see a corporation lay claim to a chunk of asteoid that nobody has ever been on or wants, than a part of the Earth, huh?<br>
<br>
<br>
 I'm looking for a good link for info on early Shuttle concepts, and that SSPS HLV design. Encyclopedia astronatuica has soome, but there used to be a great huge site with all the old iterations. (I remember line drawings in sick neon green on a black screen...)<br>
<br>
